        { type: 'paragraph', text: 'Emmanuel Levinas, Beauvoir\'s contemporary and fellow inheritor of the phenomenological tradition, mounted a profound challenge to the existentialist ethics she championed. For Levinas, the fundamental problem with Beauvoir\'s framework — and with existentialism more broadly — is that it begins from the self and its freedom. Even when Beauvoir extends her ethics outward to demand the liberation of others, she does so from the vantage point of the autonomous subject who chooses to value freedom. Levinas argued that this gets the moral order exactly backwards. Ethics does not begin with my freedom and then discover obligations to others as a secondary consequence. Rather, ethics begins with the encounter with the Other — the face of another person who addresses me with an infinite demand that I can never fully comprehend or assimilate into my own projects.' },
        { type: 'paragraph', text: 'In Levinas\'s account, the face of the Other breaks through the totalizing structures of my consciousness and confronts me with a responsibility that I did not choose and cannot refuse. This responsibility is not grounded in reciprocity or in a shared project of freedom; it is asymmetrical and infinite. I am responsible for the Other before I am responsible for myself, and this responsibility constitutes the very meaning of subjectivity. Levinas would argue that Beauvoir\'s ethics, for all its sophistication, remains trapped within what he called "the philosophy of the Same" — a tradition that subordinates otherness and alterity to the categories and projects of the knowing, free subject.' },
        { type: 'paragraph', text: 'The practical implications of this disagreement are significant. Where Beauvoir sees oppression as the denial of freedom and calls for liberation as the expansion of possibilities, Levinas sees the deeper moral failure as the refusal to be claimed by the vulnerability of the Other. For Levinas, the danger of grounding ethics in freedom is that freedom itself can become a form of violence — a way of assimilating the Other into my own world rather than allowing the Other to call my world into question. His alternative vision of ethics as infinite responsibility challenges the existentialist assumption that the free, self-determining subject is the proper starting point for moral reflection, suggesting instead that subjectivity itself is constituted by an ethical relation that precedes and exceeds any act of choice.' }
