    bio: 'Baruch (Benedict de) Spinoza was born on November 24, 1632, in Amsterdam, to a family of Portuguese Sephardic Jews who had fled the Inquisition. Raised in the vibrant Jewish community of Amsterdam, the young Spinoza received a thorough education in Hebrew, the Torah, the Talmud, and the works of medieval Jewish philosophers such as Maimonides. However, his intellectual restlessness and his engagement with the new natural philosophy of Descartes, Hobbes, and the scientific revolution led him to conclusions that his community found intolerable. In 1656, at the age of twenty-three, Spinoza was issued a cherem — a formal excommunication — by the Amsterdam Synagogue, one of the harshest ever recorded, banning all contact with him. He would never be reconciled with the Jewish community, nor would he join any Christian church, choosing instead a life of radical intellectual independence.\n\nAfter his excommunication, Spinoza earned a modest living as a lens grinder while devoting his intellectual energies to the construction of one of the most ambitious philosophical systems in Western history. His masterwork, the "Ethics, Demonstrated in Geometrical Order," was composed over many years but published only posthumously in 1677, as Spinoza rightly feared the persecution its ideas would provoke. In the "Ethics," he argued that God and Nature are one and the same infinite substance, that everything that exists follows necessarily from the divine nature, and that human freedom consists not in some illusory power of free will but in the understanding of necessity. He also produced the "Theological-Political Treatise" (1670), a groundbreaking work of biblical criticism and political philosophy that argued for freedom of thought, religious toleration, and democratic governance — ideas that were considered scandalous in his time.\n\nSpinoza lived a quiet, ascetic life in various towns in the Netherlands, sustained by a small circle of devoted friends and correspondents. His lens-grinding work exposed him to glass dust that likely contributed to the tuberculosis that would kill him at the age of forty-four on February 21, 1677. Though reviled as an atheist and heretic for over a century after his death, Spinoza\'s influence eventually proved immense, shaping the thought of figures as diverse as Goethe, Hegel, Einstein, and Deleuze. His vision of a universe governed by rational necessity, his radical monism, and his insistence that blessedness lies in the intellectual love of God-or-Nature have made him one of the most admired and debated philosophers in the entire Western tradition.',
